Primary Benefit: Contains curcumin, a powerful anti-inflammatory and antioxidant.
description: An extract from the turmeric root (Curcuma longa), standardized to contain 95% curcuminoids. Curcumin is the primary active compound in turmeric, known for its powerful antioxidant and anti-inflammatory properties. It is used to support cellular health, aid liver detoxification, and maintain cardiovascular health.[1]

Primary Benefit: Rich in beta-carotene (Vitamin A) for eye health, fiber, and antioxidants.
description: A preparation containing 10% beta-carotene, a red-orange pigment found in plants like carrots. It is a precursor to vitamin A (provitamin A), essential for vision, immune function, and skin health. It is often used as a nutritional supplement for vitamin A fortification and as a natural coloring agent in foods and beverages.

Primary Benefit: High in chlorogenic acids; aids in weight management and acts as an antioxidant.
description: A highly purified form of caffeine, a natural stimulant found in coffee, tea, and cacao plants. It is known for increasing alertness, reducing fatigue, and improving concentration by stimulating the central nervous system.

Primary Benefit: Excellent sources of proanthocyanidins, potent antioxidants that support circulation and skin health.
description: A class of potent antioxidant compounds (flavonoids) extracted from sources like grape seeds or pine bark. This 95% high-purity extract is used for its ability to protect cells from oxidative damage, support cardiovascular health, and improve circulation.

Primary Benefit: Contains berberine, which helps manage blood sugar, lower cholesterol, and fight infections.
description: A bioactive compound extracted from various plants, including Barberry and Goldenseal. It is primarily used to help maintain healthy blood sugar and cholesterol levels. It also supports metabolic health and has antimicrobial properties. The percentages indicate available concentrations.

Primary Benefit: A natural, zero-calorie sweetener that may help lower blood sugar and blood pressure.
description: A high-purity extract from the leaves of the Stevia rebaudiana plant. It contains a minimum of 95% steviol glycosides, the compounds responsible for its sweet taste. It is used as a natural, zero-calorie sweetener and sugar substitute in food and beverages.

Primary Benefit: Richest source of astaxanthin, a powerful antioxidant for skin, eye, and joint health.
description: A 10% concentration of astaxanthin, a powerful antioxidant carotenoid pigment found in microalgae, yeast, salmon, and shrimp. It is known for its ability to support skin health by protecting against UV damage, improve eye health, and reduce inflammation and oxidative stress.

Primary Benefit: Extremely high in Vitamin C; supports immune function, liver health, and hair growth.
description: An extract from the Amla fruit (Indian Gooseberry) standardized to contain 50% Vitamin C. Amla is a potent natural source of Vitamin C and antioxidants, used to boost the immune system, support healthy hair and skin, and aid digestion.

Primary Benefit: Supports eye health; protects against harmful blue light. May reduce the risk of age-related macular degeneration (AMD) and cataracts.
description: A 10% concentration of zeaxanthin, a carotenoid antioxidant that is concentrated in the macula of the human eye. It plays a crucial role in protecting the eyes from harmful high-energy blue light and reducing the risk of age-related macular degeneration and cataracts. It is often paired with lutein.

Primary Benefit: Supports eye health; works with zeaxanthin for maximum benefit. May reduce the risk of age-related macular degeneration (AMD) and cataracts.
description: A 10% concentration of lutein, a carotenoid antioxidant found in green leafy vegetables. Like zeaxanthin, it is a key component of the macular pigment in the eye, where it helps filter blue light and protects against oxidative damage, supporting overall vision health.

Primary Benefit: Supports liver health and function. Acts as an antioxidant and helps protect the liver from toxins.
description: An extract from the seeds of the Milk Thistle plant, standardized to contain 70% silymarin. Silymarin is a complex of flavonoid compounds known for its liver-protective (hepatoprotective) effects. It supports liver function, aids in detoxification, and has antioxidant properties.

Primary Benefit: Potent antioxidant and anti-inflammatory. Supports immune function, allergy relief, and cardiovascular health.
description: A highly purified plant flavonoid found in many fruits, vegetables, and grains. Quercetin is a powerful antioxidant with anti-inflammatory properties. It is used to support immune health, manage allergy symptoms, and promote cardiovascular health.

Primary Benefit: Strengthens and improves the flexibility of blood vessels, especially capillaries. Supports healthy circulation.
description: A highly purified bioflavonoid found in citrus fruits, buckwheat, and asparagus. Rutin is known for its ability to strengthen and improve the flexibility of blood vessels, particularly capillaries. It supports healthy circulation and has antioxidant and anti-inflammatory effects.

Primary Benefit: Improves blood vessel function and reduces inflammation. Often used to support circulation for conditions like venous insufficiency.
description: A 90% pure bioflavonoid extracted from the peels of citrus fruits like oranges and lemons.[14][15] It has antioxidant and anti-inflammatory properties and is commonly used to support cardiovascular health by improving circulation and strengthening blood vessels.[15][16]

Primary Benefit: Powerful antioxidant with anti-aging properties. Supports cardiovascular health and protects brain function.
description: A high-purity extract of resveratrol, a natural polyphenol found in the skin of red grapes, berries, and peanuts. It is a well-known antioxidant studied for its potential anti-aging benefits and its ability to support cardiovascular health and brain function.

Primary Benefit: Enhances the absorption and bioavailability of other nutrients, making supplements more effective.
description: An extract from black pepper (Piper nigrum) standardized to contain 95% or 10% piperine.[17][18] Piperine is the alkaloid responsible for the pungency of black pepper and is most notably used as a "bioenhancer" to significantly increase the absorption and bioavailability of other nutrients, such as curcumin.[19][20][21]

Primary Benefit: Improves vein tone and circulation. Commonly used for varicose veins and hemorrhoids, often with Hesperidine.
description: A 90% concentration of diosmin, a flavonoid compound derived from citrus fruits, particularly from hesperidin.[22][23][24] It is widely used to treat vascular conditions such as chronic venous insufficiency (CVI), varicose veins, and hemorrhoids by improving vein tone and circulation.[24][25] Often it is combined with 10% hesperidin.[16][26]

Primary Benefit: A crucial omega-3 fatty acid for brain health and cognitive function. Supports eye health and cardiovascular health.
description: A vegetarian powder containing 10% Docosahexaenoic Acid (DHA), an essential omega-3 fatty acid. This form is typically derived from microalgae. DHA is a critical component of the brain, skin, and retina, and is vital for brain development, cognitive function, and eye health.

Primary Benefit: Provides plant-based omega-3 fatty acids. Supports brain, eye, and heart health; reduces inflammation.
description: A vegetarian powder providing a 10% concentration of omega fatty acids (likely a blend of omega-3, -6, and -9). Sourced from plants like flaxseed, chia, or algae, this powder supports cardiovascular health, brain function, and helps to reduce inflammation.

Primary Benefit: Precursor to nitric oxide, which improves blood flow. Supports heart health, circulation, and athletic performance.
description: An amino acid that is a building block of protein.L-arginine is converted in the body to nitric oxide, a molecule that helps blood vessels relax and widen, thereby improving blood flow. It is used to support cardiovascular health, circulation, and athletic performance.

Primary Benefit: Hormone that regulates the natural sleep-wake cycle. Used to aid with sleep, insomnia, and jet lag.
description: A hormone produced by the brain in response to darkness that helps regulate the body's natural sleep-wake cycle (circadian rhythm). As a supplement, it is commonly used to help with sleep issues such as insomnia, jet lag, and shift work disorder.

Primary Benefit: Helps prevent and manage urinary tract infections (UTIs) by stopping bacteria from adhering to the bladder wall.
description: A type of simple sugar, related to glucose, that is found in some fruits like cranberries. It is most commonly used to help prevent and treat urinary tract infections (UTIs) by preventing certain bacteria from sticking to the walls of the urinary tract.

Primary Benefit: A dietary fiber that promotes a feeling of fullness, aiding in weight management. Supports digestive health and can help manage cholesterol levels.
description: A highly purified, natural, water-soluble dietary fiber extracted from the root of the konjac plant. Glucomannan is known for its ability to absorb large amounts of water, creating a feeling of fullness. It is used to support weight loss, manage cholesterol, and promote digestive health.

Primary Benefit: Plant sterols that help lower LDL ("bad") cholesterol by blocking its absorption in the gut.
description: A highly concentrated mixture of sterols and stanols derived from plants. Phytosterols have a structure similar to cholesterol and work by blocking the absorption of dietary cholesterol in the gut. They are used in foods and supplements to help lower LDL ("bad") cholesterol levels.

Primary Benefit: Enzyme from pineapple that aids in protein digestion. Possesses strong anti-inflammatory properties, reducing swelling and pain.
description: A complex of protein-digesting enzymes (proteases) extracted from the stem and juice of the pineapple plant. It is used as a digestive aid and is also known for its potent anti-inflammatory properties, helping to reduce swelling and pain associated with injuries and certain conditions. GDU measures enzyme activity.

Primary Benefit: Enzyme from papaya that aids in protein digestion. Helps reduce inflammation and pain.
description: A proteolytic enzyme extracted from the raw fruit of the papaya plant. Like bromelain, papain helps break down proteins and is commonly used as a digestive aid. It also has anti-inflammatory properties and is used in some topical preparations for wound healing. TU measures enzyme activity.

Primary Benefit: Rich in antioxidants, supports heart health, may improve cognitive function.
description: Acai berries are small, dark purple fruits native to the Amazon rainforest. They are lauded for their high antioxidant content, which is greater than that of cranberries, raspberries, blackberries, strawberries, or blueberries. These berries are a good source of fiber, heart-healthy fats, and calcium. Acai is often consumed as a frozen pulp, juice, or powder and is a popular ingredient in smoothie bowls, smoothies, and other health foods. Traditionally used by indigenous tribes for energy and to treat various ailments, modern uses focus on its antioxidant properties to combat cellular damage.

Primary Benefit: Potent source of Vitamin C for immune support and antioxidant protection.
description: The Acerola cherry, also known as the Barbados cherry or West Indian cherry, is a bright red fruit recognized for its exceptionally high vitamin C content. It is native to the tropical regions of the Western Hemisphere. Traditionally, it has been used to treat liver problems, diarrhea, coughs, and colds.[2] Due to its potent antioxidant properties, it is often used to prevent colds and flu and to boost the immune system. Acerola can also support skin health by promoting collagen production. The fruit can be eaten raw, but because it is highly perishable, it is more commonly available as a powder, supplement, or juice.[2]

Primary Benefit: Powerful antioxidant, supports liver health, promotes healthy hair and skin.
description: Amla, also known as Indian Gooseberry, is a small, green, tart fruit native to India. It is a nutritional powerhouse, rich in vitamin C, amino acids, and minerals. In Ayurvedic medicine, Amla has been used for thousands of years to improve digestion, boost the immune system, and promote hair growth. It is also known to have anti-inflammatory and antioxidant properties, which help protect the body from oxidative stress. Amla can be consumed fresh, juiced, powdered, or as a supplement

Primary Benefit: Supports cardiovascular health, aids in digestion, provides antioxidant benefits.[2]
description: Apples are one of the most widely cultivated tree fruits, known for their crisp texture and sweet or tart flavor. They are a good source of fiber, vitamin C, and various antioxidants. The nutrients in apples can contribute to heart health, and some studies suggest they may have a protective effect against certain types of cancer. The pectin fiber in apples acts as a prebiotic, promoting good gut bacteria. Apples are versatile and can be eaten raw, cooked in a variety of dishes, or made into juice, cider, and vinegar.

Primary Benefit: Supports eye health, provides antioxidant properties, moisturizes skin.
description: Apricots are small, golden-orange fruits with a velvety skin and flesh that is not overly juicy but rich in flavor. Originating from China, they are now grown in many temperate climates around the world. Apricots are a good source of vitamins A and C, potassium, and flavonoids, which are antioxidants that can help protect against inflammation and certain illnesses.[5][6] They are beneficial for eye health, skin protection, and digestion.[5][6] Apricots can be eaten fresh, dried, or used in jams, jellies, and desserts. Apricot oil is also used in cosmetics.[7]

Active Compound: Oleic Acid, Monounsaturated Fats, Vitamin E
Primary Benefit: Promotes heart health, supports healthy skin, rich in healthy fats.
description: Avocado is a unique fruit known for its creamy texture and rich, nutty flavor. Unlike most fruits, it is high in healthy monounsaturated fats. Avocados are also an excellent source of potassium, fiber, and vitamins K, C, E, and B-vitamins. The high fat and fiber content can help with satiety and weight management. Regular consumption may benefit heart health by improving cholesterol levels. Avocados are versatile and can be used in salads, sandwiches, smoothies, and dips like guacamole.

Primary Benefit: Supports heart health and blood pressure, provides energy, aids digestion.
description: Bananas are a popular tropical fruit known for their sweet taste and creamy texture. They are a great source of potassium, an essential mineral for maintaining normal blood pressure and heart function. Bananas also provide vitamin B6, vitamin C, and dietary fiber. The fiber in bananas can aid in digestion and promote a feeling of fullness. They are a convenient and portable snack and can be used in smoothies, baking, and desserts.

Primary Benefit: High in antioxidants and Vitamin C, supports immune function and digestion.
description: Baobab is the fruit of the Adansonia tree, native to Africa, Australia, and the Middle East. The fruit has a hard outer shell and contains a dry, powdery pulp that is rich in vitamin C, antioxidants, and several key minerals like potassium, magnesium, iron, and zinc. Baobab is often sold as a powder and can be added to foods and drinks. It is known to support the immune system, aid in digestion due to its high fiber content, and promote skin health by supporting collagen formation.

Primary Benefit: Supports vision and eye health, antioxidant properties, improves circulation.
description: Bilberry is a small, dark blue berry, similar in appearance to a blueberry, native to Northern Europe.[8] Traditionally, the dried fruit and leaves have been used for medicinal purposes.[9][10] Bilberries are rich in antioxidants, particularly anthocyanins, which are thought to be responsible for most of their health benefits.[8] They have been used for conditions related to vision and to lower blood sugar and cholesterol levels.[8][9][11] Some research suggests bilberry may help with tired or dry eyes from video monitor use.[12] Bilberry can be consumed fresh, as a jam, or as an extract in supplements.[10]

Primary Benefit: Supports joint health, may help regulate sleep cycles, antioxidant benefits.
description: Black cherry, a species native to North America, is a small, dark-colored fruit with a sweet, rich flavor. The fruit is a good source of antioxidants, including anthocyanins, which give them their deep red/purple color. These compounds have anti-inflammatory properties that may help reduce symptoms of arthritis and gout. Black cherries also contain melatonin, which may help regulate sleep cycles. They can be eaten fresh, or used in pies, jams, and juices.

Primary Benefit: Supports immune function, anti-inflammatory properties, good for eye health.
description: Black currants are small, dark purple berries with a tart flavor. They are exceptionally rich in vitamin C and are a good source of antioxidants and anthocyanins. The nutrients in black currants can help strengthen the immune system, and their anti-inflammatory properties may benefit joint health. Traditionally, they have been used to treat colds, flu, and throat infections. Black currants are often used to make juices, jams, jellies, and desserts.

Primary Benefit: Rich in antioxidants, supports brain health, may have anti-inflammatory effects.
description: Blackberries are sweet, dark-colored berries that are a good source of vitamins C and K, manganese, and fiber. They are packed with antioxidants, particularly anthocyanins, which may help reduce inflammation and protect against chronic diseases like cancer and heart disease.[13][14][15] The fiber content in blackberries aids in digestion and helps maintain healthy blood sugar levels.[13][16] Blackberries can be eaten fresh, added to yogurt and cereals, or used in desserts, jams, and smoothies. The leaf and root have also been used in traditional medicine.[14][17]

Primary Benefit: Powerful antioxidant, supports brain and eye health, may improve memory.
description: Blueberries are small, round, blue-purple berries known for being a superfood. They are low in calories but high in nutrients, including fiber, vitamin C, vitamin K, and manganese. Blueberries have one of the highest antioxidant levels among all common fruits and vegetables. These antioxidants, particularly anthocyanins, are linked to numerous health benefits, such as improved brain function, heart health, and reduced risk of chronic diseases. They can be enjoyed fresh, frozen, or in various products like jams, jellies, and baked goods.

Primary Benefit: Extremely high in Vitamin C, potent antioxidant, supports immune function.
description: Camu camu is a small, sour berry native to the Amazon rainforest. It is most famous for its incredibly high vitamin C content, containing more vitamin C than any other known food. Due to its potent antioxidant and anti-inflammatory properties, camu camu is often used to boost the immune system and support skin and gum health. Because of its very sour taste, it is rarely eaten fresh and is typically found in powder or supplement form.

Primary Benefit: Powerful antioxidant (SOD), supports skin health and hydration.
description: Cantaloupe is a type of melon with a netted, tan-colored skin and sweet, orange flesh. It is an excellent source of vitamin A (in the form of carotenoids) and vitamin C, which are important for immune function and skin health. Cantaloupe also has a high water content, making it a hydrating fruit. The potassium in cantaloupe can help maintain healthy blood pressure. It is typically eaten fresh, either on its own or in fruit salads.

Primary Benefit: Supports hormonal balance in women, may help with PMS symptoms.
description: Chasteberry is the fruit of the chaste tree and has been used for centuries in traditional medicine, particularly for women's health issues. It is often used to help regulate hormones and alleviate symptoms of premenstrual syndrome (PMS), such as bloating, irritability, and breast tenderness. It is also sometimes used to address menstrual cycle irregularities and menopausal symptoms. Chasteberry is typically taken as a liquid extract or in capsule form.

Primary Benefit: Supports urinary tract health, antioxidant properties.
description: Cranberries are small, hard, round, red fruits with a tart taste. They are well-known for their ability to help prevent urinary tract infections (UTIs) by preventing bacteria from adhering to the bladder wall. Cranberries are a good source of vitamin C and are rich in antioxidants. They may also contribute to heart health and have anti-inflammatory properties. Due to their tartness, they are rarely eaten raw and are more commonly consumed as juice, sauce, or in dried form.

Primary Benefit: Hydrating and soothing for the skin, provides antioxidant benefits.
description: Cucumbers are a widely cultivated plant in the gourd family. Though commonly considered a vegetable, they are botanically a fruit. They have a high water content (about 95%), making them very hydrating. Cucumbers contain small amounts of various nutrients, including vitamin K and antioxidants. They are often eaten raw in salads and sandwiches or pickled. Slices of cucumber are also popularly used in skincare to soothe the skin.

Primary Benefit: Natural sweetener, good source of fiber, supports digestive health.
description: Dates are the sweet, chewy fruit of the date palm tree. They are a good source of energy, fiber, and various vitamins and minerals, including potassium, magnesium, and iron. Dates are also rich in antioxidants. The fiber content can aid in digestion and help prevent constipation. They are naturally sweet and are often used as a natural sweetener in recipes or eaten on their own as a snack.

Primary Benefit: Rich in antioxidants, supports gut health with prebiotics, good source of fiber.
description: Dragon fruit, also known as pitaya, is a tropical fruit with a unique appearance, featuring a bright pink or yellow skin with green scales. The flesh, which can be white or red, is dotted with tiny black seeds and has a mildly sweet taste. It is a good source of fiber, vitamin C, and various antioxidants. Dragon fruit may help improve gut health due to its fiber content and has been noted for its potential prebiotic effects. It is typically eaten fresh.

Primary Benefit: Supports immune function, particularly for colds and flu.
description: Elderberry is the dark purple fruit of the elder tree. Historically, various parts of the elderberry tree have been used for medicinal and culinary purposes. The berries and flowers are packed with antioxidants and vitamins that may boost the immune system. Elderberry is commonly used to help prevent and ease cold and flu symptoms.[20][21] It has also been used to treat constipation and joint and muscle pain.[20][21] Raw or unripe elderberries can be toxic, so they must be cooked before consumption.[18] Elderberry is often consumed as a syrup, gummy, lozenge, pill, or tea.[20]

Primary Benefit: Aids in digestion, good source of fiber, provides antioxidant benefits.
description: Figs are a sweet fruit with a unique texture from their soft flesh and crunchy seeds. They can be eaten fresh, dried, or used in jams and baked goods. Figs are a good source of dietary fiber, which can help promote digestive health and prevent constipation. They also contain various minerals, including potassium, calcium, and magnesium.

Primary Benefit: Powerful antioxidant, supports eye health, boosts immune function.
description: Goji berries, also known as wolfberries, are small, red-orange berries that have been used in traditional Chinese medicine for centuries. They are rich in antioxidants, particularly zeaxanthin, which is beneficial for eye health. Goji berries are also a good source of vitamins A and C. They are believed to boost the immune system, support brain health, and have anti-aging properties. They can be eaten raw, cooked, or dried and are often added to cereals, trail mixes, and teas.

Primary Benefit: Supports cardiovascular health, powerful antioxidant, improves circulation.[4]
description: Grapes are berries that grow in clusters and come in various colors, including green, red, black, and purple. They are a good source of vitamins C and K, as well as antioxidants, including resveratrol, which is found in the skin of red grapes and is linked to heart health benefits. The nutrients in grapes may help protect against chronic diseases, such as heart disease and certain cancers. Grapes are eaten fresh, made into juice and wine, and dried to produce raisins.

Primary Benefit: Supports weight management, provides antioxidant benefits, antimicrobial properties.
Rich in Vitamin C, supports digestive health, antioxidant properties.
description: Guava is a tropical fruit that can be round or oval and has a green or yellow skin. The flesh can be white, pink, or red and contains small, hard seeds. Guava is exceptionally high in vitamin C, lycopene, and other antioxidants. It is also a good source of dietary fiber. The nutrients in guava can help boost immunity, benefit digestion, and promote heart health. It can be eaten fresh, juiced, or used in jams and jellies.

Primary Benefit: Supports heart health and circulation.
description: Hawthorn is a flowering shrub or tree of the rose family that produces small, berry-like fruits.[22][23] The leaves, berries, and flowers have been used in traditional medicine for centuries, particularly for heart and circulatory conditions.[23][24][25] Hawthorn contains flavonoids and other compounds with antioxidant properties.[22] It has been used to help with mild heart failure, regulate blood pressure, and manage cholesterol levels, although more research is needed to confirm these effects.[22][24][26] Hawthorn is often consumed as a tea or in supplement form.

Primary Benefit: Traditionally used as a diuretic and for digestive support.
description: Juniper berries are the female seed cones produced by various species of junipers. While they are called berries, they are not true berries in a botanical sense. They have a pungent, piney flavor and are most famously used to flavor gin. In traditional medicine, juniper berries have been used as a diuretic and to treat digestive issues. They contain compounds with antioxidant and anti-inflammatory properties. They are typically used as a spice rather than eaten as a fruit.

Primary Benefit: Aids in digestion (actinidin), high in Vitamin C for immune support.
description: Kiwifruit, or kiwi, is a small fruit with a fuzzy brown skin and bright green or golden flesh with tiny black seeds. It has a sweet and tangy flavor. Kiwi is an excellent source of vitamin C, vitamin K, and dietary fiber. The high vitamin C content helps support the immune system. The fiber in kiwi aids in digestion and can help prevent constipation. It is typically eaten fresh.

Primary Benefit: Supports immune function, aids in detoxification, provides antioxidant benefits.
description: Lemons are a citrus fruit known for their sour taste due to their high citric acid content. They are an excellent source of vitamin C and a good source of antioxidants. The vitamin C in lemons is important for immune function and skin health. Lemon juice is widely used to flavor foods and drinks. Drinking lemon water is a popular practice believed to aid digestion and detoxification, although scientific evidence for some of these claims is limited.

Primary Benefit: Supports immune health, provides antioxidant properties, good for skin health.
description: Limes are small, green citrus fruits with a tart, acidic taste. Like lemons, they are a good source of vitamin C and antioxidants. The nutrients in limes can help boost the immune system and promote healthy skin. Lime juice and zest are commonly used to add a bright, zesty flavor to a wide variety of dishes and beverages.

Primary Benefit: Natural zero-calorie sweetener, antioxidant properties.
description: Luo Han Guo, also known as monk fruit, is a small, green gourd native to Southern China. It has been used for centuries in traditional Chinese medicine. The fruit's sweetness comes from compounds called mogrosides, which are intensely sweet but contain no calories. For this reason, monk fruit sweetener is a popular natural, zero-calorie sugar substitute. It does not raise blood sugar levels, making it a good option for people with diabetes.

Primary Benefit: Antioxidant and anti-inflammatory properties, supports skin health.
description: Lychee is a tropical fruit with a rough, reddish-pink outer skin and sweet, translucent-white flesh. It is a good source of vitamin C and contains various beneficial plant compounds with antioxidant properties. These compounds may have anti-inflammatory and cardioprotective qualities.Some studies suggest that lychee may help with weight management and support brain health.[28] Lychees are typically eaten fresh but are also available canned or dried. The fruit contains chemicals that might help reduce swelling and pain and stimulate the immune system.

Primary Benefit: Antioxidant and anti-inflammatory effects, supports immune function.
description: Mango is a sweet, tropical stone fruit with a juicy, golden-yellow flesh. It is an excellent source of vitamin C and vitamin A (in the form of beta-carotene). Mangoes also contain various antioxidants. The nutrients in mangoes can support immune function, promote eye health, and aid in digestion due to their fiber content. They are eaten fresh, juiced, dried, and are a popular ingredient in smoothies, desserts, and savory dishes.

Primary Benefit: Powerful antioxidant and anti-inflammatory properties.
description: Mangosteen is a tropical fruit with a thick, purple rind and sweet, tangy, white flesh. It has been used for centuries in traditional medicine in Southeast Asia. Mangosteen is rich in a class of antioxidants called xanthones, which are believed to have potent anti-inflammatory properties. It is often consumed for its potential to boost the immune system and support overall health. The fruit is typically eaten fresh.

Primary Benefit: Supports immune function, provides antioxidant benefits, may have anti-inflammatory effects.
description: Noni is a fruit-bearing tree in the coffee family, native to Southeast Asia and Australasia. The fruit has a strong, bitter taste and has been used in traditional Polynesian medicine for thousands of years to treat a variety of health problems, including diabetes, high blood pressure, and inflammation.[32] Noni juice contains antioxidants and may support the immune system and joint health.[32][33][34] It is most commonly consumed as a juice.

Primary Benefit: Supports cardiovascular health, powerful antioxidant, anti-inflammatory properties.
description: Olives are small fruits that grow on olive trees. They are naturally very bitter and are cured before eating. Olives are a good source of healthy monounsaturated fats, specifically oleic acid, which is associated with various health benefits, including reduced inflammation. They also contain vitamin E and other antioxidants. Olives are a key component of the Mediterranean diet and are consumed whole or pressed to produce olive oil.

Primary Benefit: Supports immune function, provides antioxidant benefits, good for skin health.
description: Oranges are a popular citrus fruit known for their sweet and juicy flesh. They are most famous for their high vitamin C content, which is a powerful antioxidant that supports immune function. Oranges are also a good source of fiber, potassium, and B vitamins. The nutrients in oranges can contribute to heart health and may help prevent kidney stones. They are commonly eaten fresh or juiced.

Primary Benefit: Aids in digestion (papain), supports immune function, antioxidant properties.
description: Papaya is a tropical fruit with a soft, orange-colored flesh and a sweet, musky flavor. It is rich in an enzyme called papain, which can help break down proteins and aid in digestion. Papaya is an excellent source of vitamin C and a good source of vitamin A. It also contains antioxidants like lycopene. The nutrients in papaya can support the immune system, promote heart health, and may have anti-inflammatory effects. It is typically eaten fresh.

Primary Benefit: May promote relaxation and sleep, provides antioxidant benefits.
description: Passion fruit is a tropical fruit with a tough outer rind and a juicy, seed-filled center. It has a unique, intense, and aromatic flavor that is both sweet and tart. Passion fruit is a good source of fiber, vitamin C, and vitamin A. The fiber content is beneficial for digestive health. The fruit also contains antioxidants. The seeds are edible and are a good source of fiber. Passion fruit can be eaten fresh, juiced, or added to desserts and drinks.

Primary Benefit: Provides antioxidant benefits, supports skin health.
description: Peaches are sweet, juicy stone fruits with a fuzzy skin.[35] They are a good source of vitamins C and A, as well as potassium and fiber.[36][37] Peaches are rich in antioxidants, which can help protect the body against aging and disease.[35] Regular consumption of peaches may contribute to improved heart health, better digestion, and healthier skin.[35][38] They may also help boost the immune system and reduce inflammation.[37][38] Peaches can be eaten fresh, grilled, baked, or added to a variety of dishes.[35][37]

Primary Benefit: Aids in digestion (bromelain), anti-inflammatory properties, supports immune function.
description: Pineapple is a tropical fruit known for its distinctive appearance and sweet-tart taste. It is an excellent source of vitamin C and manganese. Pineapple contains a group of digestive enzymes called bromelain, which can help break down proteins and aid digestion. Bromelain is also known for its anti-inflammatory properties. Pineapple can be eaten fresh, canned, juiced, or used in a variety of sweet and savory dishes.

Primary Benefit: Powerful antioxidant, supports heart health, may have anti-inflammatory effects.
description: Pomegranate is a fruit containing hundreds of edible seeds called arils, which are surrounded by a sweet, juicy pulp. It is rich in powerful antioxidants, particularly punicalagins and punicic acid. These antioxidants have been linked to numerous health benefits, including reduced inflammation and a lower risk of heart disease and certain cancers. Pomegranate is typically consumed by eating the arils or drinking its juice.

Primary Benefit: Rich in antioxidants, supports weight management (raspberry ketones).
description: Raspberries are small, sweet, and slightly tart berries that are a rich source of vitamins, minerals, and antioxidants. They are particularly high in fiber and vitamin C. The antioxidants in raspberries, such as anthocyanins, may have anti-inflammatory and cancer-fighting properties. The fiber and tannins in raspberries may also help to regulate blood sugar levels. They are delicious eaten fresh, frozen, or used in jams, desserts, and smoothies.

Primary Benefit: High in Vitamin C for immune support, anti-inflammatory properties for joint health.
description: Rose hips are the small, round, seed-filled fruit of the rose plant, typically red or orange.[39][40] They are one of nature's richest sources of vitamin C and also contain vitamins A, D, and E, as well as antioxidants like flavonoids.[41] Traditionally, rose hips have been used to combat infections like coughs and colds.[41] Modern research suggests they may help reduce inflammation, which can benefit conditions like arthritis.[40][42] Rose hips are often used to make teas, jams, jellies, and supplements. Rosehip oil is also popular in skincare for its potential anti-aging properties.[39][41]

Primary Benefit: Supports prostate health in men.
description: Saw palmetto is a small palm tree native to the southeastern United States.
